<p>
  You have almost certainly worked with a PDF. They are the default format for invoices, contracts, ebooks, academic papers, government forms, and countless other documents. But what exactly <em>is</em> a PDF, and why is it the most widely used document format in the world? This guide answers everything.
</p>

<h2>What Does PDF Stand For?</h2>

<p>
  <strong>PDF stands for Portable Document Format.</strong> The name reflects its core purpose: a document format that looks exactly the same regardless of which device, operating system, or software you use to open it. A PDF created on Windows opens identically on a Mac, iPhone, or Android tablet — fonts, layouts, and images are all preserved.
</p>

<h2>Who Invented the PDF?</h2>

<p>
  Adobe Systems co-founder John Warnock conceived the PDF format in 1991 as part of an internal project called "Camelot." The problem Warnock wanted to solve was simple: how do you share a document so that anyone, anywhere, can view it exactly as intended — without needing the original software?
</p>
<p>
  Adobe released PDF publicly in 1993. For the first decade, reading a PDF required the free Adobe Acrobat Reader but creating and editing PDFs required expensive Adobe software. In 2008, Adobe released the PDF specification as an open standard. The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) then published it as <strong>ISO 32000</strong>, making PDF a truly open format that anyone can implement.
</p>

<h2>How Does a PDF File Work?</h2>

<p>
  A PDF file is a <strong>self-contained container</strong> that packages together everything needed to display a document correctly:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Text content</strong> — the actual characters and their positions on the page</li>
  <li><strong>Embedded fonts</strong> — the exact typefaces used, so text looks the same even if the font is not installed on your device</li>
  <li><strong>Images and graphics</strong> — compressed inside the file</li>
  <li><strong>Page layout information</strong> — margins, columns, headers, and footers</li>
  <li><strong>Metadata</strong> — title, author, creation date, and keywords</li>
  <li><strong>Interactive elements</strong> (in more advanced PDFs) — hyperlinks, form fields, digital signatures, bookmarks, and embedded video</li>
</ul>

<p>
  This self-contained nature is what makes PDFs "portable." Unlike a Word document that may look different depending on which fonts are installed, a PDF renders identically everywhere.
</p>

<h2>Types of PDF Files</h2>

<p>
  Not all PDFs are the same. Understanding the type of PDF you have determines what you can do with it:
</p>

<h3>Text-Based PDFs</h3>
<p>
  Created by exporting from Word, Excel, PowerPoint, or a web browser. The text is fully selectable, searchable, and extractable. These are the most common PDFs for documents, reports, and ebooks.
</p>

<h3>Scanned PDFs (Image PDFs)</h3>
<p>
  Created by scanning a physical document with a scanner or mobile app. The PDF contains images of the pages — text is not selectable or searchable unless OCR (Optical Character Recognition) is applied. Scanned PDFs are typically much larger in file size for the same content.
</p>

<h3>Interactive PDFs (PDF Forms)</h3>
<p>
  Contain fillable form fields, checkboxes, dropdown menus, and signature fields. Used for government applications, insurance forms, surveys, and contracts. Adobe Acrobat and PDF readers that support forms can fill them in digitally.
</p>

<h3>PDF/A (Archival PDF)</h3>
<p>
  A subset of PDF standardised by ISO (ISO 19005) specifically for long-term archiving. PDF/A restricts features that could make a document unreadable in the future (like encryption, external font dependencies, and embedded multimedia). Government agencies and legal institutions often require PDF/A for official filings.
</p>

<h3>PDF/X</h3>
<p>
  A subset of PDF for professional print production. Ensures all colours are correct for printing and all fonts are embedded. Used by publishers, printers, and design agencies.
</p>

