<h2>PDF vs Other Document Formats</h2>

<p>
  Why choose PDF over Word (.docx), plain text (.txt), or HTML?
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>PDF vs Word (.docx):</strong> Word documents can look different on different computers depending on which fonts are installed and which version of Word is used. PDFs always look identical. However, Word documents are much easier to edit after creation.</li>
  <li><strong>PDF vs plain text (.txt):</strong> Plain text has no formatting — no fonts, no images, no layout. PDFs preserve all visual formatting. Use plain text when formatting is irrelevant; use PDF when visual presentation matters.</li>
  <li><strong>PDF vs HTML:</strong> HTML documents are designed for the web and reflow to fit different screen sizes. PDFs have fixed-page layouts designed for a specific page size (usually A4 or US Letter). PDFs are better for print-ready documents; HTML is better for responsive web content.</li>
  <li><strong>PDF vs JPEG/PNG:</strong> Image formats only store a visual snapshot. PDFs can contain both visual output and searchable/copyable text. Use images for photographs; use PDFs for documents.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to Open a PDF</h2>

<p>
  Every major operating system and device can open PDFs natively:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Windows 10/11:</strong> Edge browser or the built-in Photos app opens PDFs by default. Adobe Acrobat Reader is a popular alternative.</li>
  <li><strong>Mac:</strong> Preview app (pre-installed) opens PDFs natively.</li>
  <li><strong>iPhone/iPad:</strong> The Files app or any web browser can open PDFs.</li>
  <li><strong>Android:</strong> Chrome browser opens PDFs. Adobe Acrobat Reader is widely used.</li>
  <li><strong>Web browser:</strong> Chrome, Firefox, Safari, and Edge all include built-in PDF viewers. You can open any PDF directly in a browser tab.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to Create a PDF</h2>

<p>
  There are several ways to create a PDF for free:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>From Word/Google Docs:</strong> File → Export → PDF (Word) or File → Download → PDF (Google Docs)</li>
  <li><strong>From any application:</strong> Print → "Save as PDF" (available on Windows, Mac, and most Linux distributions)</li>
  <li><strong>From a web page:</strong> Ctrl+P → "Save as PDF" in Chrome or Edge</li>
  <li><strong>From images:</strong> Use our free <a href="/pdfwonder/jpg-to-pdf">Image to PDF converter</a></li>
  <li><strong>From plain text:</strong> Use our free <a href="/pdfwonder/text-to-pdf">Text to PDF converter</a></li>
</ul>

